<h1>Scales</h1>
<hr/>

<p>
A scale represents a named musical scale, having a scale type (aka "mode"), and starting from a certain note (aka "root").
In general, Warp suggests defining notes and chords as {{ doc('expr_scale_notes','relative scale intervals and chords') }} versus {{ doc('expr_literal','literal notes') }}, except for percussion tracks.
Scales are fundamental to Warp as the program was largely created to improve upon the "force to scale" paradigm commonly used in other tools.
<p>

<p>
<ul>
<li>Warp ships with many pre-defined MIDI scale types</li>
<li>Users can also define their own scales by typing in a list of interval symbols: 1, 2, b3 ("flat third"), 5 ("perfect fifth"), etc.</li>
<li>Scale names used in patterns are symbolic links to the scale definition, so when you edit the parameters of a named scale (like "intro1"), they change the scale everywhere that name is used.</li>
<li>A scale may be set on the {{ doc('song') }}, or overridden on the {{ doc('scene') }} or {{ doc('clip') }}.
</ul>
</p>

